{"parse":{"title":"Canada's Golgotha","pageid":22003955,"revid":824863339,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:302px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/59/Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg/300px-Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"210\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/59/Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg/450px-Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/59/Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg/600px-Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3629\" data-file-height=\"2535\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Canada%27s_Golgotha.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A detail of the central figure of <a href=\"/wiki/Francis_Derwent_Wood\" title=\"Francis Derwent Wood\">Francis Derwent Wood</a>'s <i>Canada's Golgotha</i> (1918) at the <a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_War_Museum\" title=\"Canadian War Museum\">Canadian War Museum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ottawa\" title=\"Ottawa\">Ottawa</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ontario\" title=\"Ontario\">Ontario</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Canada\" title=\"Canada\">Canada</a></div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>Canada's Golgotha</b></i> is a 32-inch-high (810&#160;mm) bronze sculpture by the British sculptor <a href=\"/wiki/Francis_Derwent_Wood\" title=\"Francis Derwent Wood\">Francis Derwent Wood</a>, produced in 1918. It illustrates the story of <a href=\"/wiki/The_Crucified_Soldier\" title=\"The Crucified Soldier\">the Crucified Soldier</a> from the <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">First World War</a> and depicts a Canadian soldier crucified on a barn door and surrounded by jeering Germans. It is now on show at the <a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_War_Museum\" title=\"Canadian War Museum\">Canadian War Museum</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Background\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Background</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Controversy\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Controversy</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Background\">Background</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Canada%27s_Golgotha&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Background\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/The_Crucified_Soldier\" title=\"The Crucified Soldier\">The Crucified Soldier</a></div>\n<p>The story of the crucified soldier emerged in 1915, when it was claimed that a Canadian officer (later said to have been a sergeant) was crucified by German soldiers. The authenticity of the event was never established, though several soldiers claimed to have seen the body of the victim on display.\n</p><p>Two sworn statements were presented, and one from a <a href=\"/wiki/Victoria_Cross\" title=\"Victoria Cross\">Victoria Cross</a> holder attached a name to the victim: \"Sergeant Brant\". The sworn testimony from the two English soldiers, who claimed to have seen \"the corpse of a Canadian soldier fastened with bayonets to a barn door\", was subsequently debunked when it was discovered that the part of the front involved had never been occupied by Germans.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In 2002 British documentary maker <a href=\"/wiki/Iain_Overton\" title=\"Iain Overton\">Iain Overton</a> alleged that the crucified soldier did exist, and named him as Sergeant Harry Band (not \"Brant\").<sup id=\"cite_ref-natpost_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-natpost-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Controversy\">Controversy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Canada%27s_Golgotha&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Controversy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The sculpture was included in the exhibition of the Canadian War Memorial Fund collection in London, and was widely publicized before the exhibition opened. It was reproduced in more than one British newspaper, notably the <i>Daily Mail</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-evans58_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans58-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The exhibition, at <a href=\"/wiki/Burlington_House\" title=\"Burlington House\">Burlington House</a>, London, was due to open in January 1919, just before the signing of the <a href=\"/wiki/Treaty_of_Versailles\" title=\"Treaty of Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</a> and Canadian Prime Minister <a href=\"/wiki/Sir_Robert_Borden\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sir Robert Borden\">Sir Robert Borden</a> requested further investigation into the veracity of the story. At this time the German government formally requested that the Canadian government publicly acknowledge that the story of the crucified soldier was untrue, or else provide evidence. The official Canadian response to the Germans was that they had sufficient evidence to believe that the account was true, but when the Germans demanded a part in the investigation, the sculpture was withdrawn from the exhibition. It was not shown again until the 1990s.<sup id=\"cite_ref-evans58_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans58-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A <i>de facto</i> government ban on exhibiting or even photographing the sculpture was in effect as late as 1989, when a request by <a href=\"/wiki/Maria_Tippett\" title=\"Maria Tippett\">Maria Tippett</a> to include a photograph of it in an exhibition was denied.<sup id=\"cite_ref-evans58_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-evans58-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The statue was finally displayed again in 1992 in a <a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_War_Museum\" title=\"Canadian War Museum\">Canadian War Museum</a> exhibition, \"Peace Is the Dream\". The sculpture was also displayed in 2000 at an exhibition entitled \"Under the Sign of the Cross: Creative Expressions of Christianity in Canada\" at the <a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_Museum_of_Civilization\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Canadian Museum of Civilization\">Canadian Museum of Civilization</a> in 2000, when the controversy was again commented upon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\"><span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Link_rot\" title=\"Wikipedia:Link rot\"><span title=\"&#160;Dead link since February 2018\">dead link</span></a></i>&#93;</span></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Canada%27s_Golgotha&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/George_Sylvester_Viereck\" title=\"George Sylvester Viereck\">Viereck, George Sylvester</a> (1931). <i>Spreading Germs of Hate</i>. Duckworth. pp.&#160;276\u2013277.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Spreading+Germs+of+Hate&amp;rft.pages=276-277&amp;rft.pub=Duckworth&amp;rft.date=1931&amp;rft.aulast=Viereck&amp;rft.aufirst=George+Sylvester&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACanada%27s+Golgotha\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-natpost-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-natpost_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Overton, Iain (14 April 2001). \"Nurse's Note Lends Credence to Story of Crucified Soldier\". <i><a href=\"/wiki/National_Post\" title=\"National Post\">National Post</a></i>. pp.&#160;B7.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=National+Post&amp;rft.atitle=Nurse%27s+Note+Lends+Credence+to+Story+of+Crucified+Soldier&amp;rft.pages=B7&amp;rft.date=2001-04-14&amp;rft.aulast=Overton&amp;rft.aufirst=Iain&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACanada%27s+Golgotha\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-evans58-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-evans58_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-evans58_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-evans58_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Evans, Suzanne (2007). Mothers of Heroes, Mothers of Martyrs: World War I and the Politics of Grief. McGill-Queen's Press. p. 58. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-7735-3188-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-7735-3188-2\">0-7735-3188-2</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Careless, Sue (1 February 2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.anglicanjournal.com/nc/other/news-items/article/christian-artwork-exhibited-786.html\">\"Christian artwork exhibited\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Anglican_Journal\" title=\"Anglican Journal\">Anglican Journal</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved October 2012</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Christian+artwork+exhibited&amp;rft.pub=Anglican+Journal&amp;rft.date=2000-02-01&amp;rft.aulast=Careless&amp;rft.aufirst=Sue&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.anglicanjournal.com%2Fnc%2Fother%2Fnews-items%2Farticle%2Fchristian-artwork-exhibited-786.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACanada%27s+Golgotha\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Check date values in: <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;accessdate=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#bad_date\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Canada%27s_Golgotha&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"ex